            "new_string": "<p>An agent amplifies the process it is dropped into. My grandmother could cook for forty people from a recipe that lived only in her head and her wrist — \"salt as needed, cook till it is done.\" Hand that same recipe to someone who has never stood at the stove and you do not get her feast faster; you get confusion faster. An agent is the new cook. Give it a precise recipe — a crisp specification, a clear definition of done, a bounded surface — and it is magnificent. Give it the way most product decisions are actually made — a backlog of one-line tickets, tribal context, a roadmap that is really a wish-list — and it amplifies <em>that</em>. You get ambiguity, faster: the agent produces something plausible, someone has to untangle whether it was the right thing, and the round-trip eats the gain.</p>",
